V. SAFFMAN-DELBRU¨ CK FOR AN INCLUSION CURVING THE MEMBRANE

Let us ﬁnally apply our method to membrane inclusions that curve the membrane. Such particles are usually either transmembrane proteins with a conical shape that bind the surrounding lipids, thus imposing a local curvature to the membrane [36–38], or nonﬂat capping proteins adhering to the membrane [39], with the same result. Experiments have been made also with larger adhering beads [40].
